Post Script:  Damn, Bri added another post <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The definition Furt quoted is a standard set by man.  However, the laws set by man are the only laws we have.  It looks like Bri's question is, &quot;Do we have the right to execute someone who has killed another?&quot;  The only answer to that is, &quot;Yes.  The laws we have set give us that right.&quot;<br>
<br>
If you ask, &quot;Are those laws moral?&quot; I can only answer, &quot;Morality is ethereal.  Laws are concrete.  What one persons morals allow, anothers do not.&quot;<br>
<br>
I dont think we can base earthly laws on morality.  Earlier, Taino put out an example of a man being put in jail for driving without a license.  The man was legally in the wrong.  However, a persons morals might say, &quot;It was ok for him to drive because his wife was having an emergency.&quot;  Morals also might say that it is wrong for a man to have sex with a woman if they are not married.  But that is not the law.<br>
<br>
A jury is not judging the moral or ethical acts of a person.  They are simply to decide if the person acted inside or outside of the law.<br>
<br>
