<br>
As for your brother, YES it was something serious.  Twenty years ago driving drunk was no big deal.  Then, finally people started to realize how many innocent people lose their lives due to that kind of carelessness by others and it became a bigger deal.  Your brother is incredibly lucky he didn't kill someone that night.  He was fortunate that the only punishment alotted to him was a license suspension.  He was stupid to look that gift horse in the mouth regardless of the situation.  If he was as panicked as you make it sound - he probably had no business driving in that condition either - even if he'd had a license at the time.  Obviously he did something to cause him to be pulled over on the way to that emergency.  The cop didn't see him drive by and just psychically know he didn't have a license in his wallet.<br>
<br>
Should he have been treated like a criminal? Yes.  He should be treated like what he is.  He broke the law, not once, but twice.  Deprivation of books and tv?  Millions of people live that way 24/7 without breaking the law, how heartbreaking that he might miss out on a few luxuries while he's being punished for breaking the law.  He wasn't treated with respect while he was in jail?  Cry me a river, he should have thought of that before he broke the law in the first place.<br>
<br>
Regardless, your brother's self-induced situation has absolutely nothing to do with a discussion on the death penalty.  I wonder though, if your brother was lying rotting in a box underground because some other guy who had a couple beers after work and hit the brakes 2 seconds too late, would you still consider it &quot;in no way something serious&quot;?  I wonder, would you like to see the pictures of my grandfather's car, after it was T-boned by a blazer that ran a red and they used the jaws of life on it?  Would you like me to describe in detail the last 3 days of my grandfather's life, which he spent comatose in a hospital bed while we all stood around wishing for just any sign of recovery?  The guy who hit him had a bac UNDER the legal limit, and my grandfather is still dead.  The guy who killed him sent a short letter of apology to my grandmother, magnanimously admitting he shouldn't have had that beer at 10 AM, then promptly skipped town - five years later they still haven't found him.  I guess he's afraid he might spend some time not being treated with respect in jail.  In the meantime, do you think I could give a shit if this guy has lost hope and self esteem?  There is only one difference between this guy and your brother - the cops caught your brother before he registered that red light 2 seconds too late. <p><img src=http://www.kaseyspace.com/EQ/nenasig.jpg align=center>
