<br>
I believe that people are responsible for their own choices.  Yes, chemicals can and do play a part, so I'm not going to talk about those exceptions - because there are exceptions.  (I had severe post-partum after the birth of my daughter - I was able to recognize that was what it was, and that it would pass - but knowing that didn't make it go away, or make it any easier to live with).<br>
<br>
To Taino:<br>
I agree that things are never black and white, right or wrong.  I also believe that if you go back and read your posts, you saying that is somewhat hypocritical, as you take the extreme other-side of the spectrum.<br>
<br>
People own their choices.  We are free to make those choices.  There is no 'right' or 'wrong', 'black' or 'white'.  There are only better or worse, and what's better in one instance, may be worse in another.  EVERY instance must be judged individually.<br>
<br>
I grew up in a physically abusive home.  Do I beat my children?  NO!  I CHOOSE NOT TO!  That is my choice, and I own it.  Shouldn't someone with the same background who does choose to beat their children also own that choice?<br>
<br>
(I feel myself going off topic here)<br>
<br>
My opinion is that the death penalty is appropriate in some cases, and not in others, because EVERY instance is different, even when the crimes appear the same on the outside.  Rehabilitation is a wonderful thought, but it's just not going to happen in all cases, because some people will CHOOSE not to be rehabilitated.<br>
<br>
Everyone has the right to make their own choices.  We all must accept responsibility for those choices!  If we CHOOSE to go out and kill someone, we must own that choice, and whatever consequences go along with it.<br>
<br>
I see a disturbing trend arising, and that is that people are not willing to allow their children to  accept responsibility for their own actions / choices.  I see parents defending the actions of their children, and claiming the responsibility for anything from missing school to &quot;He didn't mean to hit so and so, we had a rough morning at home, and he was just displacing that anger&quot;.  This is just not right!  Not only does it teach children irresponsibility, but it takes away their RIGHT to own their choices, and understand the beauty and power of what freedom of choice give us!  The right to make a better life for ourselves. (or a worse one)<br>
<br>
Saying that someone commits a crime because one was committed against them does not make that CHOICE the better choice!  No!  People choose what they do, and how they react to every situation.<br>
<br>
It is what gives us the power to make our lives wonderful, rich, full.  (Or if you chose the contrary)<br>
<br>
<br>
---I'm afraid I have gone completely off here..  I hope you can see the point I was trying to make, and how it applies to the subject.<br>
<br>
p.s.  I know what the prisons are like here in the US.  What are they like in Sweden / other places?  Could it be that some peoples opinions about prison being enough, are based on the premise that their prison systems are more appropriate 'punishment'?  I honestly have no clue what they are like.<br>
<br>
<br>
-Eli <p><P><FONT color=#979764 face="Times New Roman" size=2><I><B>
